# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: health-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting generally follows three steps: pre-bioprinting, bioprinting, and post-bioprinting.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Pre-bioprinting is the process of creating a model that the printer will later create and choosing the materials that will be used.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] One of the first steps is to obtain a biopsy of the organ, to sample cells.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Common technologies used for bioprinting are computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] To print with a layer-by-layer approach, tomographic reconstruction is done on the images.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The now-2D images are then sent to the printer to be made.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Once the image is created, certain cells are isolated and multiplied.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] These cells are then mixed with a special liquefied material that provides oxygen and other nutrients to keep them alive.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] This aggregation of cells does not require a scaffold, and is required for placing in the tubular-like tissue fusion for processes such as extrusion.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In the second step, the liquid mixtures of cells, matrix, and nutrients known as bioinks are placed in a printer cartridge and deposited using the patients' medical scans.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] When a bioprinted pre-tissue is transferred to an incubator, this cell-based pre-tissue matures into a tissue.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting for fabricating biological constructs typically involves dispensing cells onto a biocompatible scaffold using a successive layer-by-layer approach to generate tissue-like three-dimensional structures.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Artificial organs such as livers and kidneys made by 3D bioprinting have been shown to lack crucial elements that affect the body such as working blood vessels, tubules for collecting urine, and the growth of billions of cells required for these organs.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Without these components the body has no way to get the essential nutrients and oxygen deep within their interiors.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Given that every tissue in the body is naturally composed of different cell types, many technologies for printing these cells vary in their ability to ensure stability and viability of the cells during the manufacturing process.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Some of the methods that are used for 3D bioprinting of cells are photolithography, magnetic 3D bioprinting, stereolithography, and direct cell extrusion.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The post-bioprinting process is necessary to create a stable structure from the biological material.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] If this process is not well-maintained, the mechanical integrity and function of the 3D printed object is at risk.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] To maintain the object, both mechanical and chemical stimulations are needed.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] These stimulations send signals to the cells to control the remodeling and growth of tissues.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In addition, in recent development, bioreactor technologies have allowed the rapid maturation of tissues, vascularization of tissues and the ability to survive transplants.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Bioreactors work in either providing convective nutrient transport, creating microgravity environments, changing the pressure causing solution to flow through the cells, or adding compression for dynamic or static loading.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Each type of bioreactor is ideal for different types of tissue, for example compression bioreactors are ideal for cartilage tissue.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Researchers in the field have developed approaches to produce living organs that are constructed with the appropriate biological and mechanical properties.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting is based on three main approaches: biomimicry, autonomous self-assembly and mini-tissue building blocks.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The first approach of bioprinting is called biomimicry.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The main goal of this approach is to create fabricated structures that are identical to the natural structure that are found in the tissues and organs in the human body.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Biomimicry requires duplication of the shape, framework, and the microenvironment of the organs and tissues.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The application of biomimicry in bioprinting involves creating both identical cellular and extracellular parts of organs.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] For this approach to be successful, the tissues must be replicated on a micro scale.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Therefore, it is necessary to understand the microenvironment, the nature of the biological forces in this microenvironment, the precise organization of functional and supporting cell types, solubility factors, and the composition of extracellular matrix.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The second approach of bioprinting is autonomous self-assembly.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] This approach relies on the physical process of embryonic organ development as a model to replicate the tissues of interest.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] When cells are in their early development, they create their own extracellular matrix building block, the proper cell signaling, and independent arrangement and patterning to provide the required biological functions and micro-architecture.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Autonomous self-assembly demands specific information about the developmental techniques of the tissues and organs of the embryo.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] There is a "scaffold-free" model that uses self-assembling spheroids that subjects to fusion and cell arrangement to resemble evolving tissues.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Autonomous self-assembly depends on the cell as the fundamental driver of histogenesis, guiding the building blocks, structural and functional properties of these tissues.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] It demands a deeper understanding of how embryonic tissues mechanisms develop as well as the microenvironment surrounded to create the bioprinted tissues.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The third approach of bioprinting is a combination of both the biomimicry and self-assembly approaches, called mini tissues.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Organs and tissues are built from very small functional components.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The mini-tissue approach takes these small pieces and arrange them into larger framework.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Akin to ordinary ink printers, bioprinters have three major components to them.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] These are the hardware used, the type of bio-ink, and the material it is printed on (biomaterials).
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Bio-ink is a material made from living cells that behaves much like a liquid, allowing people to 'print' it in order to create the desired shape.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] To make bio-ink, scientists create a slurry of cells that can be loaded into a cartridge and inserted into a specially designed printer, along with another cartridge containing a gel known as bio-paper.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In bioprinting, there are three major types of printers that have been used.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] These are inkjet, laser-assisted, and extrusion printers.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Inkjet printers are mainly used in bioprinting for fast and large-scale products.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] One type of inkjet printer, called drop-on-demand inkjet printer, prints materials in exact amounts, minimizing cost and waste.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Printers that use lasers provide high-resolution printing; however, these printers are often expensive.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Extrusion printers print cells layer-by-layer, just like 3D printing to create 3D constructs.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In addition to just cells, extrusion printers may also use hydrogels infused with cells.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Extrusion-based printing is a very common technique within the field of 3D printing which entails extruding, or forcing, a continuous stream of melted solid material or viscous liquid through a sort of orifice, often a nozzle or syringe.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] When it comes to extrusion based bioprinting, there are four main types of extrusion.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] These are pneumatic driven, piston driven, screw driven and eccentric screw driven (also known as progressing cavity pump).
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Each extrusion method has their own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Pneumatic extrusion uses pressurized air to force liquid bioink through a depositing agent.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Air filters are commonly used to sterilize the air before it is used, to ensure air pushing the bioink is not contaminated.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Piston driven extrusion uses a piston connected to a guide screw.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The linear motion of the piston squeezes material out of the nozzle.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Screw driven extrusion uses an auger screw to extrude material using rotational motion.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Screw driven devices allow for the use of higher viscosity materials and provide more volumetric control.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Eccentric screw driven systems allow for a much more precise deposition of low to high viscosity materials due to the self-sealing chambers in the extruder.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Once printed, many materials require a crosslinking step to achieve the desired mechanical properties for the construct, which can be achieved for example with the treatment of chemical agents or photo-crosslinkers.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Direct extrusion is one of the most common extrusion-based bioprinting techniques, wherein the pressurized force directs the bioink to flow out of the nozzle, and directly print the scaffold without any necessary casting.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The bioink itself for this approach can be a blend of polymer hydrogels, naturally derived materials such as collagen, and live cells suspended in the solution.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In this manner, scaffolds can be cultured post-print and without the need for further treatment for cellular seeding.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Some focus in the use of direct printing techniques is based upon the use of coaxial nozzle assemblies, or coaxial extrusion.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The coaxial nozzle setup enables the simultaneous extrusion of multiple material bioinks, capable of making multi-layered scaffolds in a single extrusion step.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The development of tubular structures has found the layered extrusion achieved via these techniques desirable for the radial variability in material characterization that it can offer, as the coaxial nozzle provides an inner and outer tube for bioink flow.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Indirect extrusion techniques for bioprinting rather require the printing of a base material of cell-laden hydrogels, but unlike direct extrusion contains a sacrificial hydrogel that can be trivially removed post-printing through thermal or chemical extraction.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The remaining resin solidifies and becomes the desired 3D-printed construct.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Laser-based bioprinting can be split into two major classes: those based on cell transfer technologies or photo-polymerization.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In cell transfer laser printing, a laser stimulates the connection between energy-absorbing material (e.g. gold, titanium, etc.) and the bioink.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] This 'donor layer' vaporizes under the laser's irradiation, forming a bubble from the bioink layer which gets deposited from a jet.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Photo-polymerization techniques rather use photoinitiated reactions to solidify the ink, moving the beam path of a laser to induce the formation of a desired construct.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Certain laser frequencies paired with photopolymerization reactions can be carried out without damaging cells in the material.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In this form of printing, plastic residues are melted down and individual layered in sections to create a desired shape.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Nylon and PVA are examples of biomaterials used in this method.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] This technique is most often used to design prototypes for prosthetics and cartilage construction.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Another form of bioprinting involves an inkjet printer, which is primarily used in biomedical settings.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] This method prints detailed proteins and nucleic acids.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Hydrogels are commonly selected as the bioink.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Cells can be printed on to a selected surface media to proliferate and ultimately differentiate.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] A drawback of this printing method is the ability of the bioinks such as hydrogels to clog the printing nozzle, due to their high viscosity.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Ideal inkjet bioprinting involves using a low polymer viscosity (ideally below 10 centipoise), low cell density (<10 million cells/mL), and low structural heights (<10 million cells/mL).
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] There are several other bioprinting techniques which are less commonly used.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Droplet-based bioprinting is a technique in which the bioink blend of cells and/or hydrogels are placed in droplets in precise positions.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Most common amongst this approach are thermal and piezoelectric-drop-on-demand techniques.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] This method of bioprinting is often used experimentally with lung and ovarian cancer models.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Thermal technologies use short duration signals to heat the bioink, inducing the formation of small bubbles which are ejected.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Piezoelectric bioprinting has short duration current applied to a piezoelectric actuator, which induces a mechanical vibration capable of ejecting a small globule of bioink through the nozzle.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] A significant aspect of the study of droplet-based approaches to bioprinting is accounting for mechanical and thermal stress cells within the bioink experience near the nozzle-tip as they are extruded.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Bioinks are essential components of the bioprinting process.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] They are composed of living cells and enzymatic supplements to nurture an environment that supports the biological needs of the printed tissue.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The environment created by the bioink allows for the cell to attach, grow, and differentiate into its adult form.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Cell-encapsualting hydrogels are used in extrusion based bioprinting methods, while gelatin MethacryloylGelatin methacrylon (GelMA) and acellular comprised bioinks are most often used in tissue engineering techniques that require cross-linkage and precise structural integrity.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] It is essential for bioinks to help replicate the external cellular matrix environment that the cell would naturally occur in.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting can be used to reconstruct tissue from various regions of the body.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The precursor to the adoption of 3D printing in healthcare was a series of trials conducted by researchers at Boston Children's Hospital.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The team built replacement urinary bladders by hand for seven patients by constructing scaffolds, then layering the scaffolds with cells from the patients and allowing them to grow.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The trials were a success as the patients remained in good health 7 years after implantation, which led a research fellow named Anthony Atala, MD, to search for ways to automate the process.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Patients with end-stage bladder disease can now be treated by using bio-engineered bladder tissues to rebuild the damaged organ.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] This technology can also potentially be applied to bone, skin, cartilage and muscle tissue.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Though one long-term goal of 3D bioprinting technology is to reconstruct an entire organ as well as minimize the problem of the lack of organs for transplantation.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] There has been little success in bioprinting of fully functional organs e.g. liver, skin, meniscus or pancreas.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Unlike implantable stents, organs have complex shapes and are significantly harder to bioprint.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] A bioprinted heart, for example, must not only meet structural requirements, but also vascularization, mechanical load, and electrical signal propagation requirements.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In 2022, the first success of a clinical trial for a 3D bioprinted transplant that is made from the patient's own cells, an external ear to treat microtia, was reported.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The limitations of 3D bioprinting are associated with physiologically irrelevant morphology and unsuccessful histological evaluation methods.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting contributes to significant advances in the medical field of tissue engineering by allowing for research to be done on innovative materials called biomaterials.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Some of the most notable bioengineered substances are usually stronger than the average bodily materials, including soft tissue and bone.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] These constituents can act as future substitutes, even improvements, for the original body materials.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In addition, the Defense Threat Reduction Agency aims to print mini organs such as hearts, livers, and lungs as the potential to test new drugs more accurately and perhaps eliminate the need for testing in animals.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Bioprinting can also be used for cultured meat.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In 2021, a steak-like cultured meat, composed of three types of bovine cell fibers was produced.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The Wagyu-like beef has a structure similar to original meat.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] This technology provides an alternative to natural meat harvesting methods if the livestock industry is plagued by disease.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] In addition, it provides a possible solution to reducing the environmental impact of the livestock industry.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The bioprinting of biofilms uses the same methods as other bioprinting.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Oftentimes, the biofilm begins with an extrusion of a polysaccharide to provide structure for biofilm growth.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] An example of one of these polysaccharides is alginate.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The alginate structure can have microbes embedded within the structure.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Hydrogels can also be used to assist in the formation of functional biofilms.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Biofilms are difficult to analyze in a laboratory setting due to the complex structure and the time it takes for a functional biofilm to form.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting biofilms allows us to skip certain processes and makes it easier to analyze functional biofilms.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Thickness of the biofilm being printed with change the functionality due to nutrient and oxygen diffusion.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Thicker 3D printed biofilms will naturally select for anaerobes for example.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Biofilms are capable of remediation in the natural environment which suggests there is potential in regards to the use of 3D bioprinted biofilm use in environmental remediation.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Microbes are able to degrade a large range of chemicals and metals and providing a structure for these microbes to flourish such as in biofilm structures is beneficial.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Artificial biofilms protect the microbes from the dangers of the environment while promoting signaling and overall microbial interactions.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting allows functional microorganisms to be placed in structures that provide mechanical stability and protects them from environmental conditions.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] The larger contact area provided by 3D printed structures compared to normal environmental structures provides more efficient removal of pollutants.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Bioprinting also has possible uses in the future in assisting in wastewater treatment and in corrosion control.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] When humans come in contact with environmental biofilms, it is possible for infections and long-term health hazards to occur.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Antibiotic penetration and expansion within a biofilm is an area of research which can benefit from bioprinting techniques, to further explore the effect of environmental biofilms on human health.
[src:health-system/3d-bioprinting] Biofilm printing requires further research due to limited published data and complex protocols.
[src:health-system/academic-health-science-centre] AMCs are intended to ensure that medical research breakthroughs lead to direct clinical benefits for patients.
[src:health-system/academic-health-science-centre] The organisational structures that comprise an AMCs can take a variety of forms, ranging from simple partnerships to, less frequently, fully integrated organisations with a single management board.
[src:health-system/academic-health-science-centre] There are AMCs operating in a number of countries including Australia, Canada, Ireland, Japan, the Netherlands, Qatar, Singapore, Sweden, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] Acronyms are very commonly used in healthcare settings.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] They are formed from the lead letters of words relating to medications, organisations, procedures and diagnoses.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] They come from both English and Latin roots.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] Acronyms have been described as jargon. and their use has been shown to impact the safety of patients in hospitals, owing to ambiguity and legibility.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] Acronyms in healthcare are formed from the lead letters of words relating to medications, organisations, procedures and diagnoses.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] The use of acronyms and abbreviations is expanding rapidly.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] Studies have been conducted investigating the effect of acronyms on communication and, in some studies, even healthcare professionals are unclear as to the meaning of many acronyms.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] The use of acronyms to describe medical trials has been criticised as potentially leading to incorrect assumptions based on similar acronyms, difficulty accessing trial results when common words are used, and causing a cognitive bias when positive acronyms are used to portray trials (e.g.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] Use of abbreviations, such as those relating to the route of administration or dose of a medication, can be confusing and is the most common source of medication errors.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] Use of some acronyms has been shown to impact the safety of patients in hospitals, and "do not use lists" have been published at a national level in the US.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] A number of sources provide lists of initialisms and acronyms commonly used in health care.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] The terms listed are used in the English language within the healthcare systems and by healthcare professionals of various countries.
[src:health-system/acronyms-in-healthcare] Examples of terms include BP, COPD, TIMI score, and SOAP.
[src:health-system/acute-care] Acute care services are generally delivered by teams of health care professionals from a range of medical and surgical specialties.
[src:health-system/acute-care] Acute care may require a stay in a hospital emergency department, ambulatory surgery center, urgent care centre or other short-term stay facility, along with the assistance of diagnostic services, surgery, or follow-up outpatient care in the community.
[src:health-system/acute-care] Hospital-based acute inpatient care typically has the goal of discharging patients as soon as they are deemed healthy and stable.
[src:health-system/acute-care] Acute care settings include emergency department, intensive care, coronary care, cardiology, neonatal intensive care, and many general areas where the patient could become acutely unwell and require stabilization and transfer to another higher dependency unit for further treatment.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The **Affordable Care Act** (**ACA**), formally the **Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act** (**PPACA**) and informally known as **Obamacare**, is a landmark U.S. federal statute enacted by the 111th United States Congress and signed into law by President Barack Obama on March 23, 2010.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Together with amendments made to it by the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010, it represents the U.S. healthcare system's most significant regulatory overhaul and expansion of coverage since the enactment of Medicare and Medicaid in 1965.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The ACA's major provisions came into force in 2014.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] By 2016, the uninsured share of the population had roughly halved, with estimates ranging from 20 to 24 million additional people covered.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The law also enacted delivery system reforms intended to constrain healthcare costs and improve quality.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] After it came into effect, increases in overall healthcare spending slowed, including premiums for employer-based insurance plans.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The increased coverage was due, roughly equally, to an expansion of Medicaid eligibility and changes to individual insurance markets.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Both received new spending, funded by a combination of new taxes and cuts to Medicare provider rates and Medicare Advantage.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Several Congressional Budget Office (CBO) reports stated that overall these provisions reduced the budget deficit, that repealing ACA would increase the deficit, and that the law reduced income inequality.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The act largely retained the existing structure of Medicare, Medicaid, and the employer market, but individual markets were radically overhauled.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Insurers were made to accept all applicants without charging based on pre-existing conditions or demographic status (except age).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] To combat the resultant adverse selection, the act mandated that individuals buy insurance (or pay a monetary penalty) and that insurers cover a list of "essential health benefits".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Young people were allowed to stay on their parents' insurance plans until they were 26 years old.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Before and after its enactment the ACA faced strong political opposition, calls for repeal, and legal challenges.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Supreme Court ruled that Congress cannot use the Commerce Clause to compel individuals to buy health insurance but upheld the individual mandate by recharacterizing the penalty as a tax.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Court also held that states could opt out of the ACA's Medicaid expansion without losing existing federal Medicaid funding, while otherwise upholding the law.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] This led Republican-controlled states to not participate in Medicaid expansion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Polls initially found that 43% of Americans wanted to see the law repealed or scaled back and 49% wanted to see it expanded or enacted as is.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 set the individual mandate penalty at $0 starting in 2019.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA amended the Public Health Service Act of 1944 and inserted new provisions on affordable care into Title 42 of the United States Code.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The individual insurance market was radically overhauled, and many of the law's regulations applied specifically to this market, while the structure of Medicare, Medicaid, and the employer market were largely retained.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Some regulations applied to the employer market, and the law also made delivery system changes that affected most of the health care system.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] All new individual major medical health insurance policies sold to individuals and families faced new requirements.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The requirements took effect on January 1, 2014.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The individual mandate required everyone to have insurance or pay a penalty.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The mandate and limits on open enrollment were designed to avoid the insurance death spiral, minimize the free rider problem and prevent the healthcare system from succumbing to adverse selection.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The mandate was intended to increase the size and diversity of the insured population, including more young and healthy participants to broaden the risk pool, spreading costs.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, set to $0 the penalty for not complying with the individual mandate, starting in 2019.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA mandated that health insurance exchanges be provided for each state.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The exchanges are regulated, largely online marketplaces, administered by either federal or state governments, where individuals, families and small businesses can purchase private insurance plans.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Exchanges first offered insurance for 2014.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Some exchanges also provide access to Medicaid.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] States that set up their own exchanges have some discretion on standards and prices.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] For example, states approve plans for sale, and thereby influence (through negotiations) prices.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] They can impose additional coverage requirements—such as abortion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Alternatively, states can make the federal government responsible for operating their exchanges.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Households below the federal poverty level are not eligible to receive these subsidies.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Lawful Residents and some other legally present immigrants whose household income is below 100% FPL and are not otherwise eligible for Medicaid are eligible for subsidies if they meet all other eligibility requirements.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Married people must file taxes jointly to receive subsidies.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Enrollees must have U.S. citizenship or proof of legal residency to obtain a subsidy.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The subsidies for an ACA plan purchased on an exchange stop at 400% of the federal poverty level (FPL).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] According to the Kaiser Foundation, this results in a sharp "discontinuity of treatment" at 400% FPL, which is sometimes called the "subsidy cliff".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] After-subsidy premiums for the second lowest cost silver plan (SCLSP) just below the cliff are 9.86% of income in 2019.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Subsidies are provided as an advanceable, refundable tax credit.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The amount of subsidy is sufficient to reduce the premium for the second-lowest-cost silver plan (SCLSP) on an exchange to a sliding-scale percentage of income.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The percentage is based on the percent of federal poverty level (FPL) for the household, and varies slightly from year to year.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The subsidy can be used for any plan available on the exchange, but not catastrophic plans.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The subsidy may not exceed the premium for the purchased plan.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Small businesses are eligible for a tax credit provided they enroll in the SHOP Marketplace.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] As written, ACA mandated that insurers reduce copayments and deductibles for ACA exchange enrollees earning less than 250% of the FPL.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Medicaid recipients were not eligible for the reductions.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] So-called cost-sharing reduction (CSR) subsidies were to be paid to insurance companies to fund the reductions.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] During 2017, approximately $7 billion in CSR subsidies were to be paid, versus $34 billion for premium tax credits.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The latter was defined as mandatory spending that does not require an annual Congressional appropriation.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] CSR payments were not explicitly defined as mandatory.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] This led to litigation and disruption later.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The risk-corridor program was a temporary risk management device.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] It was intended to encourage reluctant insurers into ACA insurance market from 2014 to 2016.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] For those years the Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) would cover some of the losses for insurers whose plans performed worse than they expected.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Loss-making insurers would receive payments paid for in part by profit-making insurers.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Similar risk corridors had been established for the Medicare prescription drug benefit.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] While many insurers initially offered exchange plans, the program did not pay for itself as planned, losing up to $8.3 billion for 2014 and 2015.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Authorization had to be given so DHHS could pay insurers from "general government revenues".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] However, the Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2014 stated that no funds "could be used for risk-corridor payments". leaving the government in a potential breach of contract with insurers who offered qualified health plans.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Several insurers sued the government at the United States Court of Federal Claims to recover the funds believed owed to them under the Risk Corridors program.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] While several were summarily closed, in the case of *Moda Health v the United States*, Moda Health won a $214-million judgment in February 2017.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Wheeler stated, "the Government made a promise in the risk corridors program that it has yet to fulfill.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Supreme Court reversed this ruling in the consolidated case, *Maine Community Health Options v.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] United States*, reaffirming as with Judge Wheeler that the government had a responsibility to pay those funds under the ACA and the use of riders to de-obligate its from those payments was illegal.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The temporary reinsurance program is meant to stabilize premiums by reducing the incentive for insurers to raise premiums due to concerns about higher-risk enrollees.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Reinsurance was based on retrospective costs rather than prospective risk evaluations.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Reinsurance was available from 2014 through 2016.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Risk adjustment involves transferring funds from plans with lower-risk enrollees to plans with higher-risk enrollees.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] It was intended to encourage insurers to compete based on value and efficiency rather than by attracting healthier enrollees.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Of the three risk management programs, only risk adjustment was permanent.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Plans with low actuarial risk compensate plans with high actuarial risk.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA revised and expanded Medicaid eligibility starting in 2014.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] All U.S. citizens and legal residents with income up to 133% of the poverty line would qualify for coverage in any state that participated in the Medicaid program.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Previously, states could set various lower thresholds for certain groups and were not required to cover adults without dependent children.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] A 5% "income disregard" made the effective income eligibility limit for Medicaid 138% of the poverty level.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] However, the Supreme Court ruled in *NFIB v.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Sebelius* that this provision of ACA was coercive, and that states could choose to continue at pre-ACA eligibility levels.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Income from self-employment and wages of single individuals in excess of $200,000 annually are subjected to an additional tax of 0.9%.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The threshold amount is $250,000 for a married couple filing jointly (threshold applies to their total compensation), or $125,000 for a married person filing separately.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] In ACA's companion legislation, the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010, an additional tax of 3.8% was applied to unearned income, specifically the lesser of net investment income and the amount by which adjusted gross income exceeds the above income limits.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA included an excise tax of 40% ("Cadillac tax") on total employer premium spending in excess of specified dollar amounts (initially $10,200 for single coverage and $27,500 for family coverage) indexed to inflation.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] This tax was originally scheduled to take effect in 2018, but was delayed until 2020 by the Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2016 and again to 2022.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The excise tax on high-cost health plans was completely repealed as part of H.R.1865 - Further Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2020.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Excise taxes totaling $3 billion were levied on importers and manufacturers of prescription drugs.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] An excise tax of 2.3% on medical devices and a 10% excise tax on indoor tanning services were applied as well.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The State Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) enrollment process was simplified.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Beginning September 23, 2010, dependents were permitted to remain on their parents' insurance plan until their 26th birthday, including dependents who no longer lived with their parents, are not a dependent on a parent's tax return, are no longer a student, or are married.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Businesses that employ fifty or more people but do not offer health insurance to their full-time employees are assessed additional tax if the government has subsidized a full-time employee's healthcare through tax deductions or other means.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] This is commonly known as the employer mandate.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] This provision was included to encourage employers to continue providing insurance once the exchanges began operating.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The act includes delivery system reforms intended to constrain costs and improve quality.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] These include Medicare payment changes to discourage hospital-acquired conditions and readmissions, bundled payment initiatives, the Center for Medicare and Medicaid Innovation, the Independent Payment Advisory Board, and accountable care organizations.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Health care cost/quality initiatives included incentives to reduce hospital infections, adopt electronic medical records, and to coordinate care and prioritize quality over quantity.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Medicare switched from fee-for-service to bundled payments.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] A single payment was to be paid to a hospital and a physician group for a defined episode of care (such as a hip replacement) rather than separate payments to individual service providers.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Medicare Shared Savings Program (MSSP) was established by section 3022 of the Affordable Care Act.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] It is the program by which an accountable care organization interacts with the federal government, and by which accountable care organizations can be created.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Act allowed the creation of accountable care organizations (ACOs), which are groups of doctors, hospitals and other providers that commit to give coordinated care to Medicare patients.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] ACOs were allowed to continue using fee-for-service billing.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] They receive bonus payments from the government for minimizing costs while achieving quality benchmarks that emphasize prevention and mitigation of chronic disease.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Missing cost or quality benchmarks subjected them to penalties.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Unlike health maintenance organizations, ACO patients are not required to obtain all care from the ACO.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Also, unlike HMOs, ACOs must achieve quality-of-care goals.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Medicare Part D participants received a 50% discount on brand name drugs purchased after exhausting their initial coverage and before reaching the catastrophic-coverage threshold.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] By 2020, the "doughnut hole" would be completely filled.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] From 2017 onwards, states can apply for a "waiver for state innovation" which allows them to conduct experiments that meet certain criteria.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] To obtain a waiver, a state must pass legislation setting up an alternative health system that provides insurance at least as comprehensive and as affordable as ACA, covers at least as many residents and does not increase the federal deficit.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] These states can escape some of ACA's central requirements, including the individual and employer mandates and the provision of an insurance exchange.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The state would receive compensation equal to the aggregate amount of any federal subsidies and tax credits for which its residents and employers would have been eligible under ACA, if they cannot be paid under the state plan.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Community Living Assistance Services and Supports Act (or CLASS Act) established a voluntary and public long-term care insurance option for employees, The program was abolished as impractical without ever having taken effect.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Consumer Operated and Oriented Plans (CO-OP), member-governed non-profit insurers, could start providing health care coverage, based on a 5-year federal loan.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] As of 2017, only four of the original 23 co-ops were still in operation, including Mountain Health CO-OP.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Nutrition labeling requirements officially took effect in 2010, but implementation was delayed, and they actually took effect on May 7, 2018.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] ACA followed a long series of unsuccessful attempts by one party or the other to pass major insurance reforms.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Innovations were limited to health savings accounts (2003), medical savings accounts (1996) or flexible spending accounts, which increased insurance options, but did not materially expand coverage.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Health care was a major factor in multiple elections, but until 2009, neither party had the votes to overcome the other's opposition.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The concept of an individual mandate goes back to at least 1989, when The Heritage Foundation, a conservative think-tank, proposed an individual mandate as an alternative to single-payer health care.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] It was championed for a time by conservative economists and Republican senators as a market-based approach to healthcare reform on the basis of individual responsibility and avoidance of free rider problems.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Specifically, because the 1986 Emergency Medical Treatment and Active Labor Act (EMTALA) requires any hospital participating in Medicare (nearly all do) to provide emergency care to anyone who needs it, the government often indirectly bore the cost of those without the ability to pay.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] President Bill Clinton proposed a major healthcare reform bill in 1993 that ultimately failed.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Clinton negotiated a compromise with the 105th Congress to instead enact the State Children's Health Insurance Program (SCHIP) in 1997.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The failed Clinton plan included a mandate for employers to provide health insurance to all employees through a regulated marketplace of health maintenance organizations.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Republican senators proposed an alternative that would have required individuals, but not employers, to buy insurance.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The 1993 Republican Health Equity and Access Reform Today (HEART) Act, contained a "universal coverage" requirement with a penalty for noncompliance—an individual mandate—as well as subsidies to be used in state-based 'purchasing groups'.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Advocates included prominent Republican senators such as John Chafee, Orrin Hatch, Chuck Grassley, Bob Bennett and Kit Bond.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The 1994 Republican Consumer Choice Health Security Act, initially contained an individual mandate with a penalty provision; however, author Don Nickles subsequently removed the mandate, stating, "government should not compel people to buy health insurance".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] At the time of these proposals, Republicans did not raise constitutional issues; Mark Pauly, who helped develop a proposal that included an individual mandate for George H.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Bush, remarked, "I don't remember that being raised at all.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] In 2006, an insurance expansion bill was enacted at the state level in Massachusetts.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill contained both an individual mandate and an insurance exchange.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Republican Governor Mitt Romney used a line-item veto on some provisions, and the Democratic legislature overrode some of his changes (including the mandate).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Romney's implementation of the 'Health Connector' exchange and individual mandate in Massachusetts was at first lauded by Republicans.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] During Romney's 2008 presidential campaign, Senator Jim DeMint praised Romney's ability to "take some good conservative ideas, like private health insurance, and apply them to the need to have everyone insured".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Romney said of the individual mandate: "I'm proud of what we've done.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] In 2007 Republican Senator Bob Bennett and Democratic Senator Ron Wyden introduced the Healthy Americans Act, which featured an individual mandate and state-based, regulated insurance markets called "State Health Help Agencies".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill attracted bipartisan support, but died in committee.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Many of its sponsors and co-sponsors remained in Congress during the 2008 healthcare debate.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] By 2008 many Democrats were considering this approach as the basis for healthcare reform.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Experts said the legislation that eventually emerged from Congress in 2009 and 2010 bore similarities to the 2007 bill and that it took ideas from the Massachusetts reforms.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] A driving force behind Obama's healthcare reform was Peter Orszag, Director of the Office of Management and Budget.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama called Orszag his "healthcare czar" because of his knowledge of healthcare reform.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Orszag had previously been director of the Congressional Budget Office, and under his leadership the agency had focused on using cost analysis to create an affordable and effective approach to health care reform.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Orszag claimed that healthcare reform became Obama's top agenda item because he wanted it to be his legacy.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] According to an article by Ryan Lizza in *The New Yorker*, the core of "the Obama budget is Orszag's belief [in]...a government empowered with research on the most effective medical treatments".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama bet "his presidency on Orszag's thesis of comparative effectiveness." Orszag's policies were influenced by an article in *The Annals of Internal Medicine* co-authored by Elliott S.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The article presented strong evidence based on the co-authors' research that numerous procedures, therapies and tests were being delivered with scant evidence of their medical value.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] If those procedures and tests could be eliminated, this evidence suggested, medical costs might provide the savings to give healthcare to the uninsured population.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] After reading a *New Yorker* article that used the "Dartmouth findings" to compare two counties in Texas with enormous variations in Medicare costs using hard data, Obama directed that his entire staff read it.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] More than anything else, the Dartmouth data intrigued Obama since it gave him an academic rationale for reshaping medicine.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The concept of comparing the effectiveness of healthcare options based on hard data ("comparative effectiveness" and "evidence-based medicine") was pioneered by John E.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Wennberg, founder of The Dartmouth Institute, co-founder of The Foundation for Informed Medical Decision Making and senior advisor to Health Dialog Inc., a venture that he and his researchers created to help insurers implement the Dartmouth findings.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Healthcare reform was a major topic during the 2008 Democratic presidential primaries.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] As the race narrowed, attention focused on the plans presented by the two leading candidates, Hillary Clinton and the eventual nominee, Barack Obama.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Each candidate proposed a plan to cover the approximately 45 million Americans estimated to not have health insurance at some point each year.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Clinton's proposal would have required all Americans to obtain coverage (in effect, an individual mandate), while Obama's proposal provided a subsidy without a mandate.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] During the general election, Obama said fixing healthcare would be one of his top four priorities as president.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama and his opponent, Senator John McCain, both proposed health insurance reforms, though their plans differed.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] McCain proposed tax credits for health insurance purchased in the individual market, which was estimated to reduce the number of uninsured people by about 2 million by 2018.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama proposed private and public group insurance, income-based subsidies, consumer protections, and expansions of Medicaid and SCHIP, which was estimated at the time to reduce the number of uninsured people by 33.9 million by 2018 at a higher cost.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama announced to a joint session of Congress in February 2009 his intent to work with Congress to construct a plan for healthcare reform.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] By July, a series of bills were approved by committees within the House of Representatives.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] On the Senate side, from June to September, the Senate Finance Committee held a series of 31 meetings to develop a proposal.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] This group—in particular, Democrats Max Baucus, Jeff Bingaman and Kent Conrad, along with Republicans Mike Enzi, Chuck Grassley and Olympia Snowe—met for more than 60 hours, and the principles they discussed, in conjunction with the other committees, became the foundation of a Senate bill.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] They chose this approach after concluding that filibuster-proof support in the Senate was not present for more progressive plans such as single-payer.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] By deliberately drawing on bipartisan ideas—the same basic outline was supported by former Senate Majority Leaders Howard Baker, Bob Dole, Tom Daschle and George J.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Mitchell—the bill's drafters hoped to garner the necessary votes.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] However, following the incorporation of an individual mandate into the proposal, Republicans threatened to filibuster any bill that contained it.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell, who led the Republican response, concluded Republicans should not support the bill.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Republican senators, including those who had supported earlier proposals with a similar mandate, began to describe the mandate as "unconstitutional".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] During the August 2009 summer congressional recess, many members went back to their districts and held town hall meetings on the proposals.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The nascent Tea Party movement organized protests and many conservative groups and individuals attended the meetings to oppose the proposed reforms.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Threats were made against members of Congress over the course of the debate.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] In September 2009 Obama delivered another speech to a joint session of Congress supporting the negotiations.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] On November 7, the House of Representatives passed the Affordable Health Care for America Act on a 220–215 vote and forwarded it to the Senate for passage.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Senate began work on its own proposals while the House was still working.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The United States Constitution requires all revenue-related bills to originate in the House.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] To formally comply with this requirement, the Senate repurposed H.R.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] 3590, a bill regarding housing tax changes for service members.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] It had been passed by the House as a revenue-related modification to the Internal Revenue Code.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill became the Senate's vehicle for its healthcare reform proposal, discarding the bill's original content.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill ultimately incorporated elements of proposals that were reported favorably by the Senate Health and Finance committees.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] With the Republican Senate minority vowing to filibuster, 60 votes would be necessary to pass the Senate.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] At the start of the 111th Congress, Democrats had 58 votes.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Minnesota Senate election was ultimately won by Democrat Al Franken, making 59.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Arlen Specter switched to the Democratic party in April 2009, giving them 60 seats, enough to end a filibuster.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Negotiations were undertaken attempting to satisfy moderate Democrats and to bring Republican senators aboard; particular attention was given to Republicans Bennett, Enzi, Grassley and Snowe.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] After the Finance Committee vote on October 15, negotiations turned to moderate Democrats.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid focused on satisfying centrists.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The holdouts came down to Joe Lieberman of Connecticut, an independent who caucused with Democrats, and conservative Nebraska Democrat Ben Nelson.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Lieberman's demand that the bill not include a public option was met, although supporters won various concessions, including allowing state-based public options such as Vermont's failed Green Mountain Care.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The latter half of the compromise was derisively termed the "Cornhusker Kickback" and was later removed.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] On December 23, the Senate voted 60–39 to end debate on the bill: a cloture vote to end the filibuster.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill then passed, also 60–39, on December 24, 2009, with all Democrats and two independents voting for it, and all Republicans against (except Jim Bunning, who did not vote).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The bill was endorsed by the American Medical Association and AARP.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] On January 19, 2010, Massachusetts Republican Scott Brown was elected to the Senate in a special election to replace the recently deceased Ted Kennedy, having campaigned on giving the Republican minority the 41st vote needed to sustain Republican filibusters.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Additionally, the symbolic importance of losing Kennedy's traditionally Democratic Massachusetts seat made many Congressional Democrats concerned about the political cost of the bill.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] With Democrats no longer able to get the 60 votes to break a filibuster in the Senate, White House Chief of Staff Rahm Emanuel argued that Democrats should scale back to a less ambitious bill, but House Speaker Nancy Pelosi pushed back, dismissing more moderate reform as "Kiddie Care".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama remained insistent on comprehensive reform.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The news that Anthem in California intended to raise premium rates for its patients by as much as 39% gave him new evidence of the need for reform.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] On February 22, he laid out a "Senate-leaning" proposal to consolidate the bills.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] He held a meeting with both parties' leaders on February 25.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Democrats decided the House would pass the Senate's bill, to avoid another Senate vote.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] House Democrats had expected to be able to negotiate changes in a House–Senate conference before passing a final bill.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Since any bill that emerged from conference that differed from the Senate bill would have to pass the Senate over another Republican filibuster, most House Democrats agreed to pass the Senate bill on condition that it be amended by a subsequent bill.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] They drafted the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act, which could be passed by the reconciliation process.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Per the Congressional Budget Act of 1974, reconciliation cannot be subject to a filibuster.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] But reconciliation is limited to budget changes, which is why the procedure was not used to pass ACA in the first place; the bill had inherently non-budgetary regulations.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Although the already-passed Senate bill could not have been passed by reconciliation, most of House Democrats' demands were budgetary: "these changes—higher subsidy levels, different kinds of taxes to pay for them, nixing the Nebraska Medicaid deal—mainly involve taxes and spending.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The remaining obstacle was a pivotal group of pro-life Democrats led by Bart Stupak who were initially reluctant to support the bill.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The group found the possibility of federal funding for abortion significant enough to warrant opposition.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Senate bill had not included language that satisfied their concerns, but they could not address abortion in the reconciliation bill as it would be non-budgetary.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Instead, Obama issued Executive Order 13535, reaffirming the principles in the Hyde Amendment to continue banning the use of federal funds for abortion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] This won the support of Stupak and members of his group and assured the bill's passage.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The House passed the Senate bill with a 219–212 vote on March 21, 2010, with 34 Democrats and all 178 Republicans voting against it.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] It passed the second bill, by 220–211, the same day (with the Senate passing this bill via reconciliation by 56-43 a few days later).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The day after the passage of ACA, March 22, Republicans introduced legislation to repeal it.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Obama signed ACA into law on March 23, 2010.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] Since passage, Republicans have voted to repeal all or parts of the Affordable Care Act more than sixty times.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 eliminated the fine for violating the individual mandate, starting in 2019.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] (The requirement itself is still in effect.) In 2019 Congress repealed the so-called "Cadillac" tax on health insurance benefits, an excise tax on medical devices, and the Health Insurance Tax.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] The American Rescue Plan Act of 2021, enacted during the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States, expanded subsidies for marketplace health plans.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p01] A continuation of these subsidies was introduced as part of the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The law caused a significant reduction in the number and percentage of people without health insurance.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The CDC reported that the percentage of people without health insurance fell from 16.0% in 2010 to 8.9% from January to June 2016.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The uninsured rate dropped in every congressional district in the U.S. from 2013 to 2015.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The Congressional Budget Office reported in March 2016 that approximately 12 million people were covered by the exchanges (10 million of whom received subsidies) and 11 million added to Medicaid.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Another million were covered by ACA's "Basic Health Program", for a total of 24 million.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO estimated that ACA would reduce the net number of uninsured by 22 million in 2016, using a slightly different computation for the above figures totaling ACA coverage of 26 million, less 4 million for reductions in "employment-based coverage" and "non-group and other coverage".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) estimated that 20.0 million adults (aged 18–64) gained healthcare coverage via ACA as of February 2016; similarly, the Urban Institute found in 2016 that 19.2 million non-elderly Americans gained health insurance coverage from 2010 to 2015.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2016, CBO estimated the uninsured at approximately 27 million people, or around 10% of the population or 7–8% excluding undocumented immigrants.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] States that expanded Medicaid had a 7.3% uninsured rate on average in the first quarter of 2016, while those that did not had a 14.1% uninsured rate, among adults aged 18–64.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] As of December 2016 32 states (including Washington DC) had adopted the Medicaid extension.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2017 study found that the ACA reduced socioeconomic disparities in health care access.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The Affordable Care Act reduced the percent of Americans between 18 and 64 who were uninsured from 22.3 percent in 2010 to 12.4 percent in 2016.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] About 21 million more people have coverage ten years after the enactment of the ACA.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Ten years after its enactment studies showed that the ACA also had a positive effect on health and caused a reduction in mortality.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Excise taxes from the Affordable Care Act raised $16.3 billion in fiscal year 2015. $11.3 billion came from an excise tax placed directly on health insurers based on their market share.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Annual excise taxes totaling $3 billion were levied on importers and manufacturers of prescription drugs.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The Individual mandate tax was $695 per individual or $2,085 per family at a minimum, reaching as high as 2.5% of household income (whichever was higher).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The tax was set to $0 beginning in 2019.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In the fiscal year 2018, the individual and employer mandates yielded $4 billion each.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Excise taxes on insurers and drug makers added $18 billion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Income tax surcharges produced 437 billion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] ACA reduced income inequality measured after taxes, due to the income tax surcharges and subsidies.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO estimated that subsidies paid under the law in 2016 averaged $4,240 per person for 10 million individuals receiving them, roughly $42 billion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The tax subsidy for the employer market, was approximately $1,700 per person in 2016, or $266 billion total.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] As of August 2016, 15 states operated their own health insurance marketplace.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Other states either used the federal exchange, or operated in partnership with or supported by the federal government.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] By 2019, 12 states and Washington DC operated their own exchanges.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] As of December 2019, 37 states (including Washington DC) had adopted the Medicaid extension.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Those states that expanded Medicaid had a 7.3% uninsured rate on average in the first quarter of 2016, while the others had a 14.1% uninsured rate, among adults aged 18 to 64.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Following the Supreme Court ruling in 2012, which held that states would not lose Medicaid funding if they did not expand Medicaid under ACA, several states rejected the option.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Over half the national uninsured population lived in those states.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) estimated that the cost of expansion was $6,366 per person for 2015, about 49 percent above previous estimates.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] An estimated 9 to 10 million people had gained Medicaid coverage, mostly low-income adults.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The Kaiser Family Foundation estimated in October 2015 that 3.1 million additional people were not covered because of states that rejected the Medicaid expansion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In many states income thresholds were significantly below 133% of the poverty line.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Many states did not make Medicaid available to childless adults at any income level.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Because subsidies on exchange insurance plans were not available to those below the poverty line, such individuals had no new options.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Absent children, non-disabled adults were not eligible for Medicaid there.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Studies of the impact of Medicaid expansion rejections calculated that up to 6.4 million people would have too much income for Medicaid but not qualify for exchange subsidies.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Several states argued that they could not afford the 10% contribution in 2020.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2016 study found that residents of Kentucky and Arkansas, which both expanded Medicaid, were more likely to receive health care services and less likely to incur emergency room costs or have trouble paying their medical bills.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Residents of Texas, which did not accept the Medicaid expansion, did not see a similar improvement during the same period.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Kentucky opted for increased managed care, while Arkansas subsidized private insurance.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Later Arkansas and Kentucky governors proposed reducing or modifying their programs.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] From 2013 to 2015, the uninsured rate dropped from 42% to 14% in Arkansas and from 40% to 9% in Kentucky, compared with 39% to 32% in Texas.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2016 DHHS study found that states that expanded Medicaid had lower premiums on exchange policies, because they had fewer low-income enrollees, whose health on average is worse than that of those with higher income.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In September 2019, the Census Bureau reported that states that expanded Medicaid under the ACA had considerably lower uninsured rates than states that did not.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, for adults between 100% and 399% of poverty level, the uninsured rate in 2018 was 12.7% in expansion states and 21.2% in non-expansion states.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Of the 14 states with uninsured rates of 10% or greater, 11 had not expanded Medicaid.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The drop in uninsured rates due to expanded Medicaid has broadened access to care among low-income adults, with post-ACA studies indicating an improvement in affordability, access to doctors, and usual sources of care.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Importantly, issues with cost-related unmet medical needs, skipped medications, paying medical bills, and annual out-of-pocket spending have been significantly reduced among low-income adults in Medicaid expansion states compared to non-expansion states.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] As well, expanded Medicaid has led to a 6.6% increase in physician visits by low-income adults, as well as increased usage of preventative care such as dental visits and cancer screenings among childless, low-income adults.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Improved health care coverage due to Medicaid expansion has been found in a variety of patient populations, such as adults with mental and substance use disorders, trauma patients, cancer patients, and people living with HIV.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Use of mental health treatment increased by 2.1 percentage points, from 43% to 45.1%.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Among trauma patients nationwide, the uninsured rate has decreased by approximately 50%.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Adult trauma patients in expansion states experienced a 13.7 percentage point reduction in uninsured rates compared to adult trauma patients in non-expansion states, and an accompanying 7.4 percentage point increase in discharge to rehabilitation.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Following Medicaid expansion and dependent coverage expansion, young adults hospitalized for acute traumatic injury in Maryland experienced a 60% increase in rehabilitation, 25% reduction in mortality, and a 29.8% reduction in failure-to-rescue.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The study found that a cancer diagnosis in 2014 was associated with a 1.9 percentage-point absolute and 33.5% relative decrease in uninsured rates compared to a diagnosis made between 2010 and 2013.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Another study, using Surveillance, Epidemiology, and End Results (SEER) Program data from 2010 to 2014, found that Medicaid expansion was associated with a 6.4% net increase in early stage (in situ, local, or regional) diagnoses of all cancers combined.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Expanded Medicaid coverage of PLWH has been positively associated with health outcomes such as viral suppression, retention of care, hospitalization rates, and morbidity at the time of hospitalization.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] An analysis of Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) survey data found a 2.8% annual increase in viral suppression rates among all PLWH from 2010 to 2015 due to Medicaid expansion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] As an early adopter of Medicaid expansion, Massachusetts found a 65% rate of viral suppression among all PLWH and an 85% rate among those retained in healthcare in 2014, both substantially higher than the national average.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] An analysis of hospital discharge data from 2012 to 2014 in four Medicaid expansion states and two non-expansion states revealed hospitalizations of uninsured PLWH fell from 13.7% to 5.5% in the four expansion states and rose from 14.5% to 15.7% in the two non-expansion states.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Importantly, uninsured PLWH were 40% more likely to die in the hospital than insured PLWH.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Other notable health outcomes associated with Medicaid expansion include improved glucose monitoring rates for patients with diabetes, better hypertension control, and reduced rates of major post-operative morbidity.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A July 2019 study by the National Bureau of Economic Research (NBER) indicated that states enacting Medicaid expansion exhibited statistically significant reductions in mortality rates.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] From that study, states that took Medicaid expansion "saved the lives of at least 19,200 adults aged 55 to 64 over the four-year period from 2014 to 2017." Further, 15,600 older adults died prematurely in the states that did not enact Medicaid expansion in those years according to the NBER research.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Due to many states' failure to expand, many Democrats co-sponsored the proposed 2021 Cover Now Act that would allow county and municipal governments to fund Medicaid expansion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Despite the significant increase in access to insurance coverage and healthcare services across the board, the ACA's Medicaid expansion has not fully addressed problems of economic equity.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Critics argue that Medicaid expansion has not reduced cost-sharing by a significant margin, as the amount households paid out of pocket for healthcare over the past ten years (in the form of deductibles, co-payments, etc.) rose by 77%.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Additionally, 30% of providers deny Medicaid patients, which affects the accessibility of quality care.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] This increase in denial may be in part because providers receive 62 cents from Medicaid for every dollar received from private insurers.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Studies on insurance rates show that economic inequality still persists: a significantly higher proportion of those with income greater than 100% but less than 200% of the federal poverty level were uninsured from 2010 to 2015 than of those with income greater than 200% of the federal poverty level.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] This is exacerbated by the 2012 Supreme Court decision allowing states to opt out of Medicaid, since many of the states that have opted out have more vulnerable populations, with large numbers of minorities or low-income people.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Medicaid patients have also reported receiving "second-class" treatment compared to privately insured patients, with longer wait times and lower quality of care.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] National health care expenditures rose faster than national income both before (2009–2013: 3.73%) and after (2014–2018: 4.82%) ACA's major provisions took effect.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Premium prices rose considerably before and after.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, a study published in 2016 found that the average requested 2017 premium increase among 40-year-old non-smokers was about 9 percent, although Blue Cross Blue Shield proposed increases of 40 percent in Alabama and 60 percent in Texas.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] However, some or all these costs were offset by tax credits.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, the Kaiser Family Foundation reported that for the second-lowest cost "Silver plan", a 40-year old non-smoker making $30,000 per year would pay effectively the same amount in 2017 as they did in 2016 (about $208/month) after the tax credit, despite a large increase in the list price.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In other words, the subsidies increased along with the premium price, fully offsetting the increases for subsidy-eligible enrollees.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Premium cost increases in the employer market moderated after 2009.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] For example, healthcare premiums for those covered by employers rose by 69% from 2000 to 2005, but only 27% from 2010 to 2015, with only a 3% increase from 2015 to 2016.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] From 2008 to 2010 (before passage of ACA) health insurance premiums rose by an average of 10% per year.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Several studies found that the 2008 financial crisis and accompanying Great Recession could not account for the entirety of the slowdown and that structural changes likely shared at least partial credit.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2013 study estimated that changes to the health system had been responsible for about a quarter of the recent reduction in inflation.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Paul Krawzak claimed that even if cost controls succeed in reducing the amount spent on healthcare, such efforts on their own may be insufficient to outweigh the long-term burden placed by demographic changes, particularly the growth of the population on Medicare.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A contributing factor to premium cost moderation was that the insured faced higher deductibles, copayments and out-of-pocket maximums.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In addition, many employees chose to combine a health savings account with higher deductible plans, making the net impact of ACA difficult to determine precisely.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] According to a 2014 study, ACA likely prevented an estimated 50,000 preventable patient deaths from 2010 to 2013.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Himmelstein and Woolhandler wrote in January 2017 that a rollback of ACA's Medicaid expansion alone would cause an estimated 43,956 deaths annually.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] According to the Kaiser Foundation, expanding Medicaid in the remaining states would cover up to 4.5 million persons.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2021 study found a significant decline in mortality rates in the states that opted in to the Medicaid expansion program compared with those states that did not do so.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The study reported that states decisions' not to expand Medicaid resulted in approximately 15,600 excess deaths from 2014 through 2017.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Dependent Coverage Expansion (DCE) under the ACA has had a demonstrable effect on various health metrics of young adults, a group with a historically low level of insurance coverage and utilization of care.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Studies have also found that DCE was associated with improvements in cancer prevention, detection, and treatment among young adult patients.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A study of 10,010 women aged 18–26 identified through the 2008-12 National Health Interview Survey found that the likelihood of HPV vaccination initiation and completion increased by 7.7 and 5.8 percentage points respectively when comparing before and after October 1, 2010.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A study using SEER Program data from 2007 to 2012 found a 2.7 percentage point increase in diagnosis at stage I disease for patients aged 19–25 compared with those aged 26–34 for all cancers combined.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Two 2018 *JAMA* studies found the Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program (HRRP) was associated with increased post-discharge mortality for patients hospitalized for heart failure and pneumonia.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2019 *JAMA* study found that ACA decreased emergency department and hospital use by uninsured individuals.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The HRRP was also shown to disproportionately penalize safety-net hospitals that predominately serve low-income patients.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The study concluded that the letters, sent to 3.9 million people, may have saved 700 lives.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2020 *JAMA* study found that Medicare expansion under the ACA was associated with reduced incidence of advanced-stage breast cancer, indicating that Medicaid accessibility led to early detection of breast cancer and higher survival rates.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Recent studies have also attributed to Medicaid expansion an increase in use of smoking cessation medications, cervical cancer screening, and colonoscopy, as well as an increase in the percentage of early-stage diagnosis of all cancers and the rate of cancer surgery for low-income patients.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Transition-of-care interventions and Alternative Payment Models under the ACA have also shown promise in improving health outcomes.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Post-discharge provider appointment and telephone follow-up interventions have been shown to reduce 30-day readmission rates among general medical-surgical inpatients.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Reductions in 60, 90, and 180 post-discharge day readmission rates due to transition-of-care interventions have also been demonstrated, and a reduction in 30-day mortality has been suggested.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The patient-centered medical home (PCMH) payment and care model, a team-based approach to population health management that risk-stratifies patients and provides focused care management and outreach to high-risk patients, has been shown to improve diabetes outcomes.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The ACA overall has improved coverage and care of diabetes, with a significant portion of the 3.5 million uninsured US adults aged 18–64 with diabetes in 2009-10 likely gaining coverage and benefits such as closure of the Medicaid Part D coverage gap for insulin.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The law placed relatively little burden on households in the top quintile (top 20%) outside of the top 1%.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO reported in multiple studies that ACA would reduce the deficit, and repealing it would increase the deficit, primarily because of the elimination of Medicare reimbursement cuts.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The 2011 comprehensive CBO estimate projected a net deficit reduction of more than $200 billion during the 2012–2021 period: it calculated the law would result in $604 billion in total outlays offset by $813 billion in total receipts, resulting in a $210 billion net deficit reduction.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO separately predicted that while most of the spending provisions do not begin until 2014, revenue would exceed spending in those subsequent years.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] This estimate was made prior to the Supreme Court's ruling that enabled states to opt out of the Medicaid expansion, thereby forgoing the related federal funding.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO and JCT subsequently updated the budget projection, estimating the impact of the ruling would reduce the cost estimate of the insurance coverage provisions by $84 billion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO in June 2015 forecast that repeal of ACA would increase the deficit between $137 billion and $353 billion over the 2016–2025 period, depending on the impact of macroeconomic feedback effects.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO also forecast that repeal of ACA would likely cause an increase in GDP by an average of 0.7% in the period from 2021 to 2025, mainly by boosting the supply of labor.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Although the CBO generally does not provide cost estimates beyond the 10-year budget projection period because of the degree of uncertainty involved in the projection, it decided to do so in this case at the request of lawmakers, and estimated a second decade deficit reduction of $1.2 trillion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO predicted deficit reduction around a broad range of one-half percent of GDP over the 2020s while cautioning that "a wide range of changes could occur".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2017 CBO estimated that repealing the individual mandate alone would reduce the 10-year deficit by $338 billion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The CBO cost estimates were criticized because they excluded the effects of potential legislation that would increase Medicare payments by more than $200 billion from 2010 to 2019.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] However, the so-called "doc fix" is a separate issue that would have existed with or without ACA.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The Center on Budget and Policy Priorities objected that Congress had a good record of implementing Medicare savings.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] According to their study, Congress followed through on the implementation of the vast majority of provisions enacted in the past 20 years to produce Medicare savings, although not the doc fix.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The doc fix became obsolete in 2015 when the savings provision was eliminated, permanently removing that spending restraint.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Scheiber and Cohn rejected critical assessments of the law's deficit impact, arguing that predictions were biased towards underestimating deficit reduction.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2010 David Walker said the CBO estimates were not likely to be accurate, because they were based on the assumption that the law would not change.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The employer mandate applies to employers of more than fifty where health insurance is provided only to the full-time workers.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Critics claimed it created a perverse incentive to hire part-timers instead.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] However, between March 2010 and 2014, the number of part-time jobs declined by 230,000 while the number of full-time jobs increased by two million.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In the public sector full-time jobs turned into part-time jobs much more than in the private sector.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2016 study found only limited evidence that ACA had increased part-time employment.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Several businesses and the state of Virginia added a 29-hour-a-week cap for their part-time employees, to reflect the 30-hour-or-more definition for full-time worker.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] As of 2013, few companies had shifted their workforce towards more part-time hours (4% in a survey from the Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Trends in working hours and the recovery from the Great Recession correlate with the shift from part-time to full-time work.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Other confounding impacts include that health insurance helps attract and retain employees, increases productivity and reduces absenteeism; and lowers corresponding training and administration costs from a smaller, more stable workforce.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Relatively few firms employ over 50 employees and more than 90% of them already offered insurance.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Most policy analysts (both right and left) were critical of the employer mandate provision.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The provision generated vocal opposition from business interests and some unions who were not granted exemptions.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] From the start of 2010 to November 2014, 43 hospitals in rural areas closed.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Critics claimed the new law had caused these closures.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Many rural hospitals were built using funds from the 1946 Hill–Burton Act.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Some of these hospitals reopened as other medical facilities, but only a small number operated emergency rooms (ER) or urgent care centers.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Between January 2010 and 2015, a quarter of ER doctors said they had seen a major surge in patients, while nearly half had seen a smaller increase.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Seven in ten ER doctors claimed they lacked the resources to deal with large increases in the number of patients.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The biggest factor in the increased number of ER patients was insufficient primary care providers to handle the larger number of insured.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Monuteaux at Boston Children's Hospital analyzed national emergency department visits among children aged 0 to 17 from 2009 to 2016 using the American Community Survey (ACS) and Nationwide Emergency Department Sample (NEDS).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] They found no immediate change in pediatric emergency department visit rates the year after the ACA took full effect in 2014, but the rate of change from 2014 to 2016 was significantly higher than previous rate trends, almost 10%.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Many hospitals merged and purchased physician practices, amounting to a significant consolidation of the provider industry.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] The increased market share gave them more leverage with insurers and reduced patient care options.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2015 the progressive Center for Economic and Policy Research found no evidence that companies were reducing worker hours to avoid ACA requirements for employees working more than 30 hours per week.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] CBO estimated that ACA would slightly reduce the size of the labor force and number of hours worked, as some would no longer be tethered to employers for their insurance.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Jonathan Cohn claimed that ACA's primary employment effect was to alleviate job lock and the reform's only significant employment impact was the retirement of those who were working only to stay insured.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] ACA updated a portion of the False Claims Act that the United States Supreme Court interpreted in *Graham County Soil & Water Conservation District v.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] There, the court said that a subsection giving public officials immunity to *qui tam* lawsuits for false statements in "administrative" disclosures encompassed state officials as well as federal ones.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Because of ACA, that section specifies that the immunity is limited to federal disclosures.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Public views became increasingly negative in reaction to specific plans discussed during the legislative debate over 2009 and 2010.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Some elements were more widely favored (preexisting conditions) or opposed (individual mandate).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Other polls found that people were concerned the law would cost more than projected and would not do enough to control costs.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In a 2012 poll 44% supported the law, with 56% against.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] By 75% of Democrats, 27% of Independents and 14% of Republicans favored the law.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] By party affiliation, 19% of Republicans, 27% of Independents, and 59% of Democrats favored the mandate.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Other polls showed additional provisions receiving majority support, including the exchanges, pooling small businesses and the uninsured with other consumers and providing subsidies.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In June 2013, a majority of the public (52–34%) indicated a desire for "Congress to implement or tinker with the law rather than repeal it".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] After the Supreme Court upheld the individual mandate, a 2012 poll held that "most Americans (56%) want to see critics of President Obama's health care law drop efforts to block it and move on to other national issues".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] As of October 2013, approximately 40% were in favor while 51% were against.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] About 29% of whites approved of the law, compared with 61% of Hispanics and 91% of African Americans.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A solid majority of seniors opposed the idea and a solid majority of those under forty were in favor.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2014 poll reported that 26% of Americans support ACA.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A later 2014 poll reported that 48.9% of respondents had an unfavorable view of ACA versus 38.3% who had a favorable view (of more than 5,500 individuals).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Another held that 8% of respondents agreed the Affordable Care Act "is working well the way it is".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In late 2014, a Rasmussen poll reported Repeal: 30%, Leave as is: 13%, Improve: 52%.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] In 2015, a poll reported that 47% of Americans approved the health care law.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] This was the first time a major poll indicated that more respondents approved than disapproved.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A December 2016 poll reported that: a) 30% wanted to expand what the law does; b) 26% wanted to repeal the entire law; c) 19% wanted to move forward with implementing the law as it is; and d) 17% wanted to scale back what the law does, with the remainder undecided.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Separate polls from Fox News and NBC/*WSJ*, both taken during January 2017, indicated more people viewed the law favorably than did not for the first time.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] One of the reasons for the improving popularity of the law is that Democrats who had once opposed it (many still prefer "Medicare for all") shifted their positions because ACA was under threat of repeal.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] Another January 2017 poll reported that 35% of respondents believed "Obamacare" and the "Affordable Care Act" were different or did not know.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] A 2017 study found that personal experience with public health insurance programs led to greater support for the ACA, most prominently among Republicans and low-information voters.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] By the end of 2023, a Morning Consult poll of registered voters found that 57% approved of the Affordable Care Act, while 30% disapproved of it.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p02] 85% of Democrats, 56% of independents, and 28% of Republicans supported the law.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The term "Obamacare" was originally coined by opponents as a pejorative.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] According to research by Elspeth Reeve, the expression was used in early 2007, generally by writers describing the candidate's proposal for expanding coverage for the uninsured.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The term officially emerged in March 2007 when healthcare lobbyist Jeanne Schulte Scott wrote, "We will soon see a 'Giuliani-care' and 'Obama-care' to go along with 'McCain-care', 'Edwards-care', and a totally revamped and remodeled 'Hillary-care' from the 1990s".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In May 2007, Mitt Romney introduced it to political discourse, saying, "How can we get those people insured without raising taxes and without having government take over healthcare?' And let me tell you, if we don't do it, the Democrats will.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] If the Democrats do it, it will be socialized medicine; it'll be government-managed care.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] By mid-2012, Obamacare had become the colloquial term used both by supporters and opponents.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Obama eventually endorsed the nickname, saying, "I have no problem with people saying Obama cares.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] I do care." By 2016 Obama explicitly and repeatedly referred to the ACA as "Obamacare".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] On August 7, 2009, Sarah Palin created the term "death panels" to describe groups who would decide whether sick patients were "worthy" of medical care.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] "Death panel" referred to two claims about early drafts.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] One was that under the law, seniors could be denied care due to their age and the other that the government would advise seniors to end their lives instead of receiving care.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The ostensible basis of these claims was the provision for an Independent Payment Advisory Board (IPAB).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] IPAB was given the authority to recommend cost-saving changes to Medicare by facilitating the adoption of cost-effective treatments and cost-recovering measures when statutory expenditure levels were exceeded within any given three-year period.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In fact, the Board was prohibited from recommending changes that would reduce payments before 2020, and was prohibited from recommending changes in premiums, benefits, eligibility and taxes, or other changes that would result in rationing.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2010, the Pew Research Center reported that 85% of Americans were familiar with the claim, and 30% believed it was true, backed by three contemporaneous polls.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The allegation was named PolitiFact's 2009 "Lie of the Year", one of FactCheck.org's "whoppers" and the most outrageous term by the American Dialect Society.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] AARP described such rumors as "rife with gross—and even cruel—distortions".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA requires members of Congress and their staffs to obtain health insurance either through an exchange or some other program approved by the law (such as Medicare), instead of using the insurance offered to federal employees (the Federal Employees Health Benefits Program).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA explicitly denies insurance subsidies to "unauthorized (illegal) aliens".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Opponents claimed that combining immediate coverage with no provision for preexisting conditions would lead people to wait to get insured until they got sick.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The individual mandate was designed to push people to get insured without waiting.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In the years after 2013, many insurers did leave specific marketplaces, claiming the risk pools were too small.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Five states had one insurer in 2017, 13 had two, 11 had three; the remainder had four or more.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Obama's previous unambiguous assurance that consumers could keep their own plans became a focal point for critics, who challenged his truthfulness.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Various bills were introduced in Congress to allow people to keep their plans.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] PolitiFact initially cited various estimates that only about 2% of the total insured population (4 million out of 262 million) received such notices, but readers later voted Obama's claims as the 2013 "Lie of the Year".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Opposition and efforts to repeal the legislation have drawn support from sources that include labor unions, conservative advocacy groups, Republicans, small business organizations and the Tea Party movement.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] These groups claimed the law would disrupt existing health plans, increase costs from new insurance standards, and increase the deficit.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Some opposed the idea of universal healthcare.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] President Donald Trump repeatedly promised to "repeal and replace" it.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In October 2016, Mark Dayton, the governor of Minnesota, said ACA had "many good features" but it was "no longer affordable for increasing numbers of people"; he called on the state legislature to provide emergency relief to policyholders.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Dayton later said he regretted his remarks after they were seized on by Republicans seeking to repeal the law.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Some pointed out that the previous system also had socialist aspects.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Even for-profit private health insurance companies socialize risk and redistribute wealth from people who have it (all premium payers) to those who need it (by paying for medically necessary healthcare).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The requirement to provide emergency care also forced redistribution from people who pay insurance premiums to those who choose to be uninsured, when they visit the emergency room.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Milos Forman opined that critics "falsely equate Western European-style socialism, and its government provision of social insurance and health care, with Marxist–Leninist totalitarianism".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Opponents challenged ACA's constitutionality in multiple lawsuits on multiple grounds.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Supreme Court ruled, 5–4, that the individual mandate was constitutional when viewed as a tax, although not under the Commerce Clause.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA withheld all Medicaid funding from states declining to participate in the expansion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Court ruled that this was unconstitutionally coercive and that individual states had the right to opt out without losing preexisting Medicaid funding.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Various lawsuits addressed these concerns, including *Burwell v.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Hobby Lobby Stores, Inc.*, which looked at private corporations and their duties under the ACA.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In *Little Sisters of the Poor Saints Peter and Paul Home v.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Pennsylvania*, the Supreme Court ruled 7–2 on July 8, 2020, that employers with religious or moral objections to contraceptives can exclude such coverage from an employee's insurance plan.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Writing for the majority, Justice Clarence Thomas said, "No language in the statute itself even hints that Congress intended that contraception should or must be covered.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] It was Congress, not the [administration], that declined to expressly require contraceptive coverage in the ACA itself." Justices Roberts, Alito, Gorsuch, and Kavanaugh joined Thomas's opinion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Justice Elena Kagan filed a concurring opinion in the judgment, in which Stephen Breyer joined.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Biden administration planned to seek a hold on O'Connor's decision.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Supreme Court ruled, 6–3, that federal subsidies for health insurance premiums could be used in the 34 states that did not set up their own insurance exchanges.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] House Republicans sued the Obama administration in 2014, alleging that cost-sharing reduction subsidy payments to insurers were unlawful because Congress had not appropriated funds to pay for them.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The argument classified the CSR subsidy as discretionary spending subject to annual appropriation.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In May 2016, a federal judge ruled for the plaintiffs, but the Obama administration appealed.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Later, President Trump ended the payments.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The House sued the administration, alleging that the money for CSRs to insurers had not been appropriated, as required for any federal government spending.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The ACA subsidy that helps customers pay premiums was not part of the suit.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Without the CSRs, the government estimated that premiums would increase by 20% to 30% for silver plans.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2017, the uncertainty about whether the payments would continue caused Blue Cross Blue Shield of North Carolina to try to raise premiums by 22.9% the next year, as opposed to an increase of 8.8% that it would have sought if the payments were assured.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Collyer ruled that the cost-sharing program was unconstitutional for spending money that has not been specifically provided by an act of Congress, but concluded that Congress had in fact authorized that program to be created.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The judge also found that Congress had provided authority to cover the spending for the tax credits to consumers who use them to help afford health coverage.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Collyer enjoined further cost-sharing payments, but stayed the order pending appeal to the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The case ended in a settlement before the Circuit Court.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Department of Justice said it would no longer defend the ACA in court, but 17 states led by California stepped in to do so.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] O'Connor's decision regarding severability turned on several passages from the Congressional debate that focused on the importance of the mandate.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] While he ruled the law unconstitutional, he did not overturn the law.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The intervening states appealed the decision to the Fifth Circuit.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] These states argued that Congress's change in the tax was only reducing the amount of the tax, and that Congress had the power to write a stronger law to this end.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] O'Connor stayed his decision pending the appeal.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Fifth Circuit heard the appeal on July 9, 2019; in the interim, the U.S.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Department of Justice joined with Republican states to argue that the ACA was unconstitutional, while the Democratic states were joined by the Democrat-controlled U.S.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] An additional question was addressed, as the Republican plaintiffs challenged the Democratic states' standing to defend the ACA.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In December 2019, the Fifth Circuit agreed the individual mandate was unconstitutional, but did not agree that the entire law should be voided.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Instead, it remanded the case to the District Court for reconsideration of that question.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Supreme Court accepted the case in March 2020, to be heard in the 2020–2021 term, with the ruling likely falling after the 2020 elections.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Democrats pointed out that the effect of invalidating the entire law would be to remove popular provisions such as the protection for preexisting conditions, and that the Republicans had still not offered any replacement plan—important issues in the 2020 elections.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] On June 17, 2021, the Court rejected the challenge in a 7–2 decision, ruling that Texas and the other plaintiff states did not have standing to challenge the provision, leaving the full ACA intact.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In April 2024, the Biden administration issued a final rule implementing Section 1557 of the ACA, adding gender identity to Title IX's definition of discrimination based on sex.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In May 2024, 15 states led by Tennessee sued HHS in the U.S.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] District Court for the Southern District of Mississippi, arguing that the 2024 rule violated the Administrative Procedure Act and the U.S.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In October 2025, a federal judge struck down the 2024 rule to the extent that it prohibits discrimination against transgender people in education and health-care programs.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Supreme Court ruled that promised risk corridor payments must be made even in the absence of specific appropriation of money by Congress.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Officials in Texas, Florida, Alabama, Wyoming, Arizona, Oklahoma and Missouri opposed those elements over which they had discretion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] For example, Missouri declined to expand Medicaid or establish a health insurance marketplace engaging in active non-cooperation, enacting a statute forbidding any state or local official to render any aid not specifically required by federal law.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Other Republicans discouraged efforts to advertise the law's benefits.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Some conservative political groups launched ad campaigns to discourage enrollment.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] ACA was the subject of many unsuccessful repeal efforts by Republicans in the 111th, 112th, and 113th Congresses: Representatives Steve King and Michele Bachmann introduced bills in the House to repeal the ACA the day after it was signed, as did Senator Jim DeMint in the Senate.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2011, after Republicans gained control of the House, one of the first votes held was on a bill titled "Repealing the Job-Killing Health Care Law Act" (H.R.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] All Republicans and three Democrats voted for repeal.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In the Senate, the bill was offered as an amendment to an unrelated bill, but was voted down.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] President Obama said he would veto the bill had it passed.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] On February 3, 2015, the House of Representatives added its 67th repeal vote to the record (239 to 186).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Strong partisan disagreement in Congress prevented adjustments to the Act's provisions.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] But at least one change, a proposed repeal of a tax on medical devices, received bipartisan support.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Some Congressional Republicans argued against improvements to the law on the grounds that they would weaken the arguments for repeal.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Republicans attempted to defund the ACA's implementation, and in October 2013 House Republicans refused to fund the federal government unless it came with an implementation delay, after Obama unilaterally deferred the employer mandate by one year, which critics claimed he had no power to do.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The House passed three versions of a bill funding the government while submitting various versions that would repeal or delay the ACA, with the last version delaying enforcement of the individual mandate.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Democratic Senate leadership said the Senate would pass only a bill without any restrictions on ACA.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The government shutdown lasted from October 1 to October 17.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] During a midnight congressional session starting January 11, the Senate of the 115th Congress of the United States voted to approve a "budget blueprint" that would allow Republicans to repeal parts of the law "without threat of a Democratic filibuster".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The plan, which passed 51–48, was named by Senate Republicans the "Obamacare 'repeal resolution.'" Democrats opposing the resolution staged a protest during the vote.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] House Republicans announced their replacement, the American Health Care Act, on March 6.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] On March 24, the AHCA failed amid a revolt among Republican representatives.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] On May 4 the House voted to pass the AHCA by a margin of 217 to 213.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Senate Republican leadership announced that Senate Republicans would write their own version of the bill instead of voting on the House version.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Leader McConnell named a group of 13 Republicans to draft the substitute version in private, raising bipartisan concerns about lack of transparency.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] On June 22, Republicans released the first discussion draft, which renamed it the "Better Care Reconciliation Act of 2017" (BCRA).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] On July 25, although no amendment proposal had garnered majority support, Republicans voted to advance the bill to the floor and begin formal consideration of amendments.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Senators Susan Collins and Lisa Murkowski were the only two dissenting Republicans, making the vote a 50–50 tie.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Vice President Mike Pence then cast the tie-breaking vote in the affirmative.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] A subsequent "Obamacare Repeal and Reconciliation Act" abandoned the "repeal and replace" approach in favor of a straight repeal, but that too failed, 45–55.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Finally, the "Health Care Freedom Act", nicknamed "skinny repeal" because it would have made the least change to ACA, failed by 49–51, with Collins, Murkowski, and McCain joining all Democrats and independents in voting against it.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Donald Trump, who has historically opposed the ACA, said during the 2024 United States presidential debates that he had "concepts of a plan" to modify or scrap it.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] JD Vance has said that Trump intends to allow insurance companies to discriminate against people with preexisting conditions or disability, with subsidized insurance replaced with private insurance.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Kamala Harris said during her 2024 campaign that she would "maintain and grow" the ACA.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] During the 2025 federal government shutdown, the ACA once again became a focal point of partisan disagreement.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] On November 8–9, 2025, as the shutdown reached its 39th day, President Donald Trump urged Senate Republicans to redirect federal funds used for ACA insurance subsidies toward direct cash payments to individuals, framing the proposal as a strategy to resolve the budgetary impasse.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Several Republican senators expressed openness to the idea; Democrats rejected it.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Analysts noted that the proposal lacked the bipartisan support necessary to reopen the federal government.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Contemporary reports described the dispute over the ACA's subsidy structure as one of the key issues contributing to the protracted shutdown.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Trump said he believed the law will expire once its tax credit is eliminated and not renewed.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The disagreement focused on whether to continue the enhanced premium tax credits expanded under previous legislation, including the American Rescue Plan, which lowered the portion of health insurance costs consumers pay.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Observers noted that if these subsidies expired, many individuals could face significant premium increases, potentially more than doubling for some enrollees.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] This raised concerns about decreased enrollment in the ACA marketplaces, especially among individuals who previously received little or no subsidy.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In addition to the effects on consumers, small businesses and self-employed individuals relying on ACA marketplace plans faced potential financial strain.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Reports also highlighted that certain federal health agency employees were furloughed during the shutdown, temporarily affecting the oversight and administration of health programs.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The debate over ACA funding illustrated how federal budget impasses can have immediate effects on both insurance markets and the delivery of health services.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Under both the ACA (current law) and the AHCA, the CBO reported that the health exchange marketplaces would remain stable.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] But Republican politicians took a variety of steps to undermine it, creating uncertainty that adversely impacted enrollment and insurer participation while increasing premiums.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Concern about the exchanges became another argument for reforms.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In December 2009, former DNC chairman and former Vermont governor Howard Dean called the ACA "a bigger bailout for the insurance industry than AIG" and "an insurance company's dream".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] He viewed the bill's end form as a death of the health care reform effort.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In his 2011 book *Remedy and Reaction*, Paul Starr, the former senior advisor for Bill Clinton's health care reform plan, notes that the ACA did not make health insurance a right and did not make medical care free at the point of service.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] He criticizies the ACA on the grounds that some lower-income individuals still cannot afford treatment and go without care "if health care and insurance are treated as ordinary commodities".
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The ACA's critics often cite its inability to control costs and lower deductibles, the difficulty for average people to compare plans, lack of a strong public option, and inadequate regulations on or alternatives (such as co-operatives) to large corporate health care companies.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2010 small business tax credits took effect.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Then Pre-Existing Condition Insurance Plan (PCIP) took effect to offer insurance to those who had been denied coverage by private insurance companies because of a preexisting condition.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] By 2011, insurers had stopped marketing child-only policies in 17 states, as they sought to escape this requirement.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In *National Federation of Independent Business v.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Sebelius* the Supreme Court allowed states to opt out of the Medicaid expansion.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In 2013, the Internal Revenue Service ruled that the cost of covering only the individual employee would be considered in determining whether the cost of coverage exceeded 9.5% of income.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Family plans would not be considered even if the cost was above the 9.5% income threshold.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] On July 2 Obama delayed the employer mandate until 2015.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The launch for both the state and federal exchanges was beset by management and technical failings.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] HealthCare.gov, the website that offers insurance through the exchanges operated by the federal government, crashed on opening and suffered many problems.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Operations stabilized in 2014, although not all planned features were complete.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Government Accountability Office released a non-partisan study in 2014 that concluded the administration had not provided "effective planning or oversight practices" in developing the exchanges.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Hobby Lobby* the Supreme Court exempted closely held corporations with religious convictions from the contraception rule.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] At the beginning of the 2015, 11.7 million had signed up (ex-Medicaid).
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] By the end of the year about 8.8 million consumers had stayed in the program.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] Congress repeatedly delayed the onset of the "Cadillac tax" on expensive insurance plans first until 2020 and later until 2022 and repealed it in late 2019.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] An estimated 9 to 10 million people had gained Medicaid coverage in 2016, mostly low-income adults.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The five major national insurers expected to lose money on ACA policies in 2016, in part because the enrollees were lower income, older and sicker than expected.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] More than 9.2 million people (3.0 million new customers and 6.2 million returning) enrolled on the national exchange in 2017, down some 400,000 from 2016.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] This decline was due primarily to the election of President Trump.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The eleven states that run their own exchanges signed up about 3 million more.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The IRS announced that it would not require that tax returns indicate a person has health insurance, reducing the effectiveness of the individual mandate, in response to Trump's executive order.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The CBO reported in March that the healthcare exchanges were expected to be stable.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] In May the House voted to repeal the ACA using the American Health Care Act (AHCA), but the AHCA was defeated in the Senate.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act set the individual mandate penalty at $0 starting in 2019.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The CBO estimated that the change would cause 13 million fewer people to have health insurance in 2027.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The 2017 Individual Market Stabilization Bill was proposed to fund cost-sharing reductions, provide more flexibility for state waivers, allow a new "Copper Plan" offering only catastrophic coverage, allow interstate insurance compacts, and redirect consumer fees to states for outreach.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] By 2019, 35 states and the District of Columbia had either expanded coverage via traditional Medicaid or via an alternative program.
[src:health-system/affordable-care-act-p03] The show aired another sketch in September 2013 with Jay Pharoah as President Obama rolling out the plan to the public, and Aaron Paul and other cast members playing ordinary Americans helping him in advocating for the legislation.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] Outdoor air pollution comes from burning fossil fuels for electricity and transport, wildfires, some industrial processes, waste management, demolition and agriculture.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] Indoor air pollution is often from burning firewood or agricultural waste for cooking and heating.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] Other sources of air pollution include dust storms and volcanic eruptions.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] Many sources of local air pollution, especially burning fossil fuels, also release greenhouse gases that cause global warming.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] However, air pollution may limit warming locally.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] Air pollution kills 7 to 8 million people each year.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] It is a significant risk factor for a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), asthma, coronavirus and lung cancer.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] Particulate matter is the most deadly, both for indoor and outdoor air pollution.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] Ozone affects crops, and forests are damaged by the pollution that causes acid rain.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] Overall, the World Bank has estimated that welfare losses (premature deaths) and productivity losses (lost labor) caused by air pollution cost the world economy over $8 trillion per year.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] Various technologies and strategies reduce air pollution.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] Key approaches include clean cookers, fire protection, improved waste management, dust control, industrial scrubbers, electric vehicles and renewable energy.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] National air quality laws have often been effective, notably the 1956 Clean Air Act in Britain and the 1963 US Clean Air Act.
[src:health-system/air-pollution] International efforts have had mixed results: the Montreal Protocol almost eliminated harmful ozone-depleting chemicals, while international action on climate change has been less successful.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] In providing care to patients with certain illnesses, AHPs may work in the public or private sector, in hospitals or in other types of facilities, and often in clinical collaboration with other providers having complementary scopes of practice.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Allied health professions are usually of smaller size proportional to physicians and nurses.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] It has been estimated that approximately 30% of the total health workforce worldwide are AHPs.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] In most jurisdictions, AHPs are subject to health professional requisites including minimum standards for education, regulation and licensing.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] They must work based on scientific principles and within an evidence-based practice model.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] They may sometimes be considered to perform the role of mid-level practitioners, when having an advanced education and training to diagnose and treat patients, but not the certification of a physician.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Allied health professionals are different from alternative medicine practitioners, also sometimes called natural healers, who work outside the conventions of modern biomedicine.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] The allied health professions represent a large cluster of health and care service providers, which usually require specific training and/or certification, but which are distinct from the medicine, nursing and dentistry professions.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] There is a large demand for allied health professionals, especially in rural and medically underserved areas.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] AHPs are generally considered distinct from other healthcare service providers on the basis of several factors.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] The precise titles, roles and requisites of AHPs vary considerably from country to country.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] In South Africa, AHPs are identified and regulated through the Health Professions Council of South Africa (e.g., clinical technologists, dental therapists) or through the Allied Health Professions Council (e.g., massage therapists, chiropractors).
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Depending on the country and local health care system, the professions that are considered AHPs vary.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] For example, in some contexts optometrists are not considered AHPs, as the profession has a longer history of primary care practice independent of modern medicine, whereas in others optometrists are identified as falling under the AHP umbrella.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Similarly, in some health care jurisdictions physiotherapists are not considered AHPs, as they tend to have more autonomy in private practice without the need for medical referral, whereas in other jurisdictions physiotherapists are identified and regulated as AHPs.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Some allied health professions are more specialized, and so must adhere to national training and education standards and their professional scope of practice.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Often they must prove their skills through degrees, diplomas, certified credentials, and continuing education.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Other allied health professions require no special training or credentials and are trained for their work by their employer through on-the-job training (which would then exclude them from consideration as an allied health profession in a country like Australia).
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Many allied health jobs are considered career ladder jobs because of the opportunities for advancement within specific fields.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Allied health professions can include the use of many skills.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] The explosion of scientific knowledge that followed World War II brought increasingly sophisticated and complex medical diagnostic and treatment procedures.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Changes in the health industry and emphasis on cost-efficient solutions to health care delivery will continue to encourage expansion of the allied health workforce.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] The World Health Organization estimates there is currently a worldwide shortage of about 2 million allied health professionals (considering all health workers aside from medical and nursing personnel) needed in order to meet global health goals.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] In recognition of the growth of the number and diversity of allied health professionals in recent years, the 2008 version of the International Standard Classification of Occupations increased the number of groups dedicated to allied health professions.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Depending on the presumed skill level, they may either be identified as "health professionals" or "health associate professionals".
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] With growing demand for ambulatory health care, researchers expect to witness a heavier demand for professions that are employed outside of hospital settings — including allied health.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] In the United Kingdom there are 14 distinct professions who are considered allied health professionals; in combination they account for about 6% of the NHS workforce.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] In 2013 the annual expenditure on services provided by allied health professionals amounted to around £2 billion, although there is a lack of evidence around the extent to which these services improve the quality of care.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] In the United States, the Association of Schools of Allied Health Professionals uses wording from the Public Health Service Act to list those who are considered to be allied health professionals.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Projections in the United States and many other countries have shown an expected long-term shortage of qualified workers to fill many allied health positions.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Studies have also pointed to the need for increased diversity in the allied health workforce to realize a culturally competent health system.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Workforce and health care experts anticipate that health services will increasingly be delivered via ambulatory and nursing care settings rather than in hospitals.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] In the US, a larger proportion of the allied health care workforce is already employed in ambulatory settings.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] In California, nearly half (49.4 percent) of the allied health workforce is employed in ambulatory health care settings, compared with 28.7 percent and 21.9 percent employed in hospital and nursing care, respectively.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] One source reported allied health professionals making up 60 percent of the total US health workforce.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] Advancements in medical technology also allow for more services that formerly required expensive hospital stays to be delivered via ambulatory care.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] For example, in California, research has predicted the total consumption of hospital days per person will decline from 4 days in 2010 to 3.2 days in 2020 to 2.5 days in 2030.
[src:health-system/allied-health-professions] In contrast, the number of ambulatory visits per person will increase from 3.2 visits per person in 2010 to 3.6 visits per person in 2020 to 4.2 visits in 2030.
[src:health-system/health-system] A **health system**, **health care system**, or **healthcare system**, is a set of organizations, institutions and resources whose primary goal is to produce actions for the promotion, restoration or maintenance of health.
[src:health-system/health-system] There is a wide variety of health systems around the world, with as many histories and organizational structures as there are countries.
[src:health-system/health-system] Implicitly, countries must design and develop health systems in accordance with their needs and resources, although common elements in virtually all health systems are primary healthcare and public health measures.
[src:health-system/health-system] In certain countries, the orchestration of health system planning is decentralized, with various stakeholders in the market assuming responsibilities.
[src:health-system/health-system] Nevertheless, it is noteworthy that the process of healthcare planning is frequently characterized as an evolutionary progression rather than a revolutionary transformation.
[src:health-system/health-system] As with other social institutional structures, health systems are likely to reflect the history, culture and economics of the states in which they evolve.
[src:health-system/health-system] These peculiarities bedevil and complicate international comparisons and preclude any universal standard of performance.
[src:health-system/health-system] According to the World Health Organization (WHO), the directing and coordinating authority for health within the United Nations system, healthcare systems' goals are good health for the citizens, responsiveness to the expectations of the population, and fair means of funding operations.
[src:health-system/health-system] Progress towards them depends on how systems carry out four vital functions: provision of health care services, resource generation, financing, and stewardship.
[src:health-system/health-system] Other dimensions for the evaluation of health systems include quality, efficiency, acceptability, and equity.
[src:health-system/health-system] They have also been described in the United States as "the five C's": Cost, Coverage, Consistency, Complexity, and Chronic Illness.
[src:health-system/health-system] Also, continuity of health care is a major goal.
[src:health-system/health-system] There are many ways to understand health systems.
[src:health-system/health-system] All of them are key to help understand their functions and elements, as well as the relationships between them.
[src:health-system/health-system] These frameworks, besides, can serve as guides to analyze and study specific health systems and their performance, in all their complexity.
[src:health-system/health-system] In 2000, the World Health Organization proposed a clear health system framework in the annual World Health Report.
[src:health-system/health-system] It featured 4 functions (stewardship, creating resources, financing, and delivering services), together with three objectives (responsiveness, fair financial contribution, and health).
[src:health-system/health-system] In 2007, this initial model evolved towards the most common health system framework to date: the "building blocks" framework.
[src:health-system/health-system] The World Bank, in 2004, published a health system framework that, despite not being as widely adopted by the international community, also had a significant impact: the "Control Knobs" model.
[src:health-system/health-system] In this framework, its authors suggested that action could be taken in five different dimensions or control knobs of the health system: financing, payment, organization, regulation, and behavior.
[src:health-system/health-system] Depending on how these knobs where turned, they would have an effect on the efficiency, quality, and access of the system.
[src:health-system/health-system] Improved performance at this level would help improve health status, customer satisfaction and risk protection, the three performance goals of the health system.
[src:health-system/health-system] Most countries' systems feature a mix of all five models.
[src:health-system/health-system] One study based on data from the OECD concluded that all types of health care finance "are compatible with" an efficient health system.
[src:health-system/health-system] The study also found no relationship between financing and cost control.
[src:health-system/health-system] Another study examining single payer and multi payer systems in OECD countries found that single payer systems have significantly less hospital beds per 100,000 people than in multi payer systems.
[src:health-system/health-system] The term health insurance is generally used to describe a form of insurance that pays for medical expenses.
[src:health-system/health-system] It is sometimes used more broadly to include insurance covering disability or long-term nursing or custodial care needs.
[src:health-system/health-system] It may be provided through a social insurance program, or from private insurance companies.
[src:health-system/health-system] It may be obtained on a group basis (e.g., by a firm to cover its employees) or purchased by individual consumers.
[src:health-system/health-system] In each case premiums or taxes protect the insured from high or unexpected health care expenses.
[src:health-system/health-system] Through the calculation of the comprehensive cost of healthcare expenditures, it becomes feasible to construct a standard financial framework, which may involve mechanisms like monthly premiums or annual taxes.
[src:health-system/health-system] This ensures the availability of funds to cover the healthcare benefits delineated in the insurance agreement.
[src:health-system/health-system] Typically, the administration of these benefits is overseen by a government agency, a nonprofit health fund, or a commercial corporation.
[src:health-system/health-system] Many commercial health insurers control their costs by restricting the benefits provided, by such means as deductibles, copayments, co-insurance, policy exclusions, and total coverage limits.
[src:health-system/health-system] They will also severely restrict or refuse coverage of pre-existing conditions.
[src:health-system/health-system] Many government systems also have co-payment arrangements but express exclusions are rare or limited because of political pressure.
[src:health-system/health-system] The larger insurance systems may also negotiate fees with providers.
[src:health-system/health-system] Many forms of social insurance systems control their costs by using the bargaining power of the community they are intended to serve to control costs in the health care delivery system.
[src:health-system/health-system] They may attempt to do so by, for example, negotiating drug prices directly with pharmaceutical companies, negotiating standard fees with the medical profession, or reducing unnecessary health care costs.
[src:health-system/health-system] Social systems sometimes feature contributions related to earnings as part of a system to deliver universal health care, which may or may not also involve the use of commercial and non-commercial insurers.
[src:health-system/health-system] Essentially the wealthier users pay proportionately more into the system to cover the needs of the poorer users who therefore contribute proportionately less.
[src:health-system/health-system] There are usually caps on the contributions of the wealthy and minimum payments that must be made by the insured (often in the form of a minimum contribution, similar to a deductible in commercial insurance models).
[src:health-system/health-system] For example, as of June 2011, Unitaid had collected more than one billion dollars from 29 member countries, including several from Africa, through an air ticket solidarity levy to expand access to care and treatment for HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria in 94 countries.
[src:health-system/health-system] In most countries, wage costs for healthcare practitioners are estimated to represent between 65% and 80% of renewable health system expenditures.
[src:health-system/health-system] There are three ways to pay medical practitioners: fee for service, capitation, and salary.
[src:health-system/health-system] There has been growing interest in blending elements of these systems.
[src:health-system/health-system] Fee-for-service arrangements pay general practitioners (GPs) based on the service.
[src:health-system/health-system] They are even more widely used for specialists working in ambulatory care.
[src:health-system/health-system] In capitation payment systems, GPs are paid for each patient on their "list", usually with adjustments for factors such as age and gender.
[src:health-system/health-system] According to OECD, "capitation systems allow funders to control the overall level of primary health expenditures, and the allocation of funding among GPs is determined by patient registrations".
[src:health-system/health-system] However, under this approach, GPs may register too many patients and under-serve them, select the better risks and refer on patients who could have been treated by the GP directly.
[src:health-system/health-system] Freedom of consumer choice over doctors, coupled with the principle of "money following the patient" may moderate some of these risks.
[src:health-system/health-system] In several OECD countries, general practitioners (GPs) are employed on *salaries* for the government.
[src:health-system/health-system] In recent years, providers have been switching from fee-for-service payment models to a value-based care payment system, where they are compensated for providing value to patients.
[src:health-system/health-system] In this system, providers are given incentives to close gaps in care and provide better quality care for patients.
[src:health-system/health-system] Sound information plays an increasingly critical role in the delivery of modern health care and efficiency of health systems.
[src:health-system/health-system] Health informatics – the intersection of information science, medicine and healthcare – deals with the resources, devices, and methods required to optimize the acquisition and use of information in health and biomedicine.
[src:health-system/health-system] Necessary tools for proper health information coding and management include clinical guidelines, formal medical terminologies, and computers and other information and communication technologies.
[src:health-system/health-system] The kinds of health data processed may include patients' medical records, hospital administration and clinical functions, and human resources information.
[src:health-system/health-system] The use of health information lies at the root of evidence-based policy and evidence-based management in health care.
[src:health-system/health-system] Increasingly, information and communication technologies are being utilised to improve health systems in developing countries through: the standardisation of health information; computer-aided diagnosis and treatment monitoring; informing population groups on health and treatment.
[src:health-system/health-system] The management of any health system is typically directed through a set of policies and plans adopted by government, private sector business and other groups in areas such as personal healthcare delivery and financing, pharmaceuticals, health human resources, and public health.
[src:health-system/health-system] Public health is concerned with threats to the overall health of a community based on population health analysis.
[src:health-system/health-system] The population in question can be as small as a handful of people, or as large as all the inhabitants of several continents (for instance, in the case of a pandemic).
[src:health-system/health-system] Public health is typically divided into epidemiology, biostatistics and health services.
[src:health-system/health-system] Environmental, social, behavioral, and occupational health are also important subfields.
[src:health-system/health-system] Today, most governments recognize the importance of public health programs in reducing the incidence of disease, disability, the effects of ageing and health inequities, although public health generally receives significantly less government funding compared with medicine.
[src:health-system/health-system] For example, most countries have a vaccination policy, supporting public health programs in providing vaccinations to promote health.
[src:health-system/health-system] Vaccinations are voluntary in some countries and mandatory in some countries.
[src:health-system/health-system] Some governments pay all or part of the costs for vaccines in a national vaccination schedule.
[src:health-system/health-system] The rapid emergence of many chronic diseases, which require costly long-term care and treatment, is making many health managers and policy makers re-examine their healthcare delivery practices.
[src:health-system/health-system] An important health issue facing the world currently is HIV/AIDS.
[src:health-system/health-system] Another major public health concern is diabetes.
[src:health-system/health-system] In 2006, according to the World Health Organization, at least 171 million people worldwide had diabetes.
[src:health-system/health-system] Its incidence is increasing rapidly, and it is estimated that by 2030, this number will double.
[src:health-system/health-system] A controversial aspect of public health is the control of tobacco smoking, linked to cancer and other chronic illnesses.
[src:health-system/health-system] Antibiotic resistance is another major concern, leading to the reemergence of diseases such as tuberculosis.
[src:health-system/health-system] The World Health Organization, for its World Health Day 2011 campaign, called for intensified global commitment to safeguard antibiotics and other antimicrobial medicines for future generations.
[src:health-system/health-system] Since 2000, more and more initiatives have been taken at the international and national levels in order to strengthen national health systems as the core components of the global health system.
[src:health-system/health-system] Having this scope in mind, it is essential to have a clear, and unrestricted, vision of national health systems that might generate further progress in global health.
[src:health-system/health-system] The elaboration and the selection of performance indicators are indeed both highly dependent on the conceptual framework adopted for the evaluation of the health systems performance.
[src:health-system/health-system] Like most social systems, health systems are complex adaptive systems where change does not necessarily follow rigid management models.
[src:health-system/health-system] In complex systems path dependency, emergent properties and other non-linear patterns are seen, which can lead to the development of inappropriate guidelines for developing responsive health systems.
[src:health-system/health-system] An increasing number of tools and guidelines are being published by international agencies and development partners to assist health system decision-makers to monitor and assess health systems strengthening including human resources development using standard definitions, indicators and measures.
[src:health-system/health-system] In response to a series of papers published in 2012 by members of the World Health Organization's Task Force on Developing Health Systems Guidance, researchers from the Future Health Systems consortium argue that there is insufficient focus on the 'policy implementation gap'.
[src:health-system/health-system] Recognizing the diversity of stakeholders and complexity of health systems is crucial to ensure that evidence-based guidelines are tested with requisite humility and without a rigid adherence to models dominated by a limited number of disciplines.
[src:health-system/health-system] Healthcare services often implement Quality Improvement Initiatives to overcome this policy implementation gap.
[src:health-system/health-system] Although many of these initiatives deliver improved healthcare, a large proportion fail to be sustained.
[src:health-system/health-system] Numerous tools and frameworks have been created to respond to this challenge and increase improvement longevity.
[src:health-system/health-system] One tool highlighted the need for these tools to respond to user preferences and settings to optimize impact.
[src:health-system/health-system] HPSR focuses on low- and middle-income countries and draws on the relativist social science paradigm which recognises that all phenomena are constructed through human behaviour and interpretation.
[src:health-system/health-system] In using this approach, HPSR offers insight into health systems by generating a complex understanding of context in order to enhance health policy learning.
[src:health-system/health-system] HPSR calls for greater involvement of local actors, including policy makers, civil society and researchers, in decisions that are made around funding health policy research and health systems strengthening.
[src:health-system/health-system] Health systems can vary substantially from country to country, and in the last few years, comparisons have been made on an international basis.
[src:health-system/health-system] The World Health Organization, in its *World Health Report 2000*, provided a ranking of health systems around the world according to criteria of the overall level and distribution of health in the populations, and the responsiveness and fair financing of health care services.
[src:health-system/health-system] The goals for health systems, according to the WHO's *World Health Report 2000 – Health systems: improving performance* (WHO, 2000), are good health, responsiveness to the expectations of the population, and fair financial contribution.
[src:health-system/health-system] There have been several debates around the results of this WHO exercise, and especially based on the country ranking linked to it, insofar as it appeared to depend mostly on the choice of the retained indicators.
[src:health-system/health-system] Direct comparisons of health statistics across nations are complex.
[src:health-system/health-system] The Commonwealth Fund, in its annual survey, "Mirror, Mirror on the Wall", compares the performance of the health systems in Australia, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Germany, Canada and the United States.
[src:health-system/health-system] Its 2007 study found that, although the United States system is the most expensive, it consistently underperforms compared to the other countries.
[src:health-system/health-system] A major difference between the United States and the other countries in the study is that the United States is the only country without universal health care.
[src:health-system/health-system] The OECD also collects comparative statistics, and has published brief country profiles.
[src:health-system/health-system] Health Consumer Powerhouse makes comparisons between both national health care systems in the Euro health consumer index and specific areas of health care such as diabetes or hepatitis.
[src:health-system/health-system] Ipsos MORI produces an annual study of public perceptions of healthcare services across 30 countries.
[src:health-system/health-system] Physicians and hospital beds per 1000 inhabitants vs Health Care Spending in 2008 for OECD Countries.
[src:health-system/health-system] Since 2008, the US experienced big deviations from 16% GDP.
[src:health-system/health-system] In 2010, the year the Affordable Care Act was enacted, health care spending accounted for approximately 17.2% of the U.S.
[src:health-system/health-system] By 2019, before the pandemic, it had risen to 17.7%.
[src:health-system/health-system] During the COVID-19 pandemic, this percentage jumped to 18.8% in 2020, largely due to increased health care costs and economic contraction.
[src:health-system/health-system] Post-pandemic, health care spending relative to GDP declined to 16.6% by 2022.
